Exploring the Natural Disasters Dataset¶

1. Introduction¶

With climate change on the rise the predictability of natural disasters has been quite challenging and their occurrences are on the rise. In 2020, California was hit with the largest number of forest fires. There were 1.2 million tons of particles released in the air. San Francisco residents experienced an orange sky from the convergence of wildfire smoke and fog.

That was only the west coast, the east coast experienced tropical storms and hurricanes in 2020.

There were billions of dollars spent and thousands of deaths.

Getting Started with the Data¶

EXTRACTING FEMA DATA¶

First, I extract data(formatted as a csvfile) on FemaWebDisasterDeclarations from fema.gov. This dataset includes a list of areas that were affected by a disaster and the kind of disaster assistance the area was eligible for.

In [2]:
data = pd.read_csv("https://www.fema.gov/api/open/v1/FemaWebDisasterDeclarations.csv")

Analysis¶

Looking at the disasters over the years we notice that earthquakes have been pretty consistent since 1950. Fires have increased and so has the number of ear

What kind of disasters occur in what regions ?¶

I am particularly interested in the major disasters that have occured. I will look at a California and New York. My main question is what kind of disasters occur in west vs. east coast and what is their occurence?

In [19]:
# Filtering major disasters in California and counting types of incidents
data1 = top_10_disastersData
# west_coast_major_disasters = data1.loc[data1['declarationType'] == 'Emergency']
west_coast_major_disasters = data1.loc[(data1['stateCode'] == 'CA') | (data1['stateCode'] == 'OR') | (data1['stateCode'] == 'WA')]
CA_counts = west_coast_major_disasters['incidentType'].value_counts()
CA_disastorTypes = list(CA_counts.index)
CA_countsArr = list(CA_counts.array)

# Filtering major disasters in New York and counting types of incidents
# east_coast_major_disasters = data1.loc[data1['declarationType'] == 'Emergency']
east_coast_major_disasters = data1.loc[(data1['stateCode'] == 'ME') | (data1['stateCode'] == 'VT') | (data1['stateCode'] == 'NH') | (data1['stateCode'] == 'CT') | (data1['stateCode'] == 'MA') | (data1['stateCode'] == 'RI') | (data1['stateCode'] == 'NY') | (data1['stateCode'] == 'MD') | (data1['stateCode'] == 'NJ') | (data1['stateCode'] == 'PA') | (data1['stateCode'] == 'VA') | (data1['stateCode'] == 'NC') | (data1['stateCode'] == 'SC') | (data1['stateCode'] == 'GA') | (data1['stateCode'] == 'FL')]
NY_counts = east_coast_major_disasters['incidentType'].value_counts()
NY_disastorTypes = list(NY_counts.index)
NY_countsArr = list(NY_counts.array)

# Drawing the bar chart
plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = (20,10)
plt.rcParams.update({'font.size': 14})

# Pairing each disaster with state gdp 2 years later 

# Creating new column in us disasters dataframe

# data = top_10_disastersData[top_10_disastersData['year'] <= 2020]
data['futureGDP'] = pd.Series(dtype='float')
data['currentGDP'] = pd.Series(dtype='float')

# Looping over the rows and adding the respective gdp 2 years later
for index, row in data.iterrows():
  state = row['stateName']
  year = row['year'] - 1
  
  # Getting current GDP
  currentGDP = states_gdp[(states_gdp['GeoName'] == state) & (states_gdp['year'] == year)]
  currentGDP = currentGDP['value']

  # Getting GDP 1 year later
  year = row['year']
  gdp_2_years_later = states_gdp[(states_gdp['GeoName'] == state) & (states_gdp['year'] == year)]
  gdp_2_years_later = gdp_2_years_later['value']

  # if gdp_2_years_later == nan:
  #   data['GDP 2 years later'][index] = np.nan
  # else:
  data['futureGDP'][index] = gdp_2_years_later
  data['currentGDP'][index] = currentGDP
